A colorful, vibrant illustration of various fun objects like a lightbulb, a magnifying glass, and a playful character, all suggesting curiosity and knowledge.

Fun Facts Compendium: Page 1
Animal Oddities
* A group of flamingos is called a flamboyance.
* The only mammal that can truly fly is the bat.
* The heart of a shrimp is located in its head.
* Did you know that a snail can sleep for three years?


 A group of vibrant pink flamingos standing together in shallow water, illustrating a flamboyance.

Space Wonders
* There are more trees on Earth than stars in the Milky Way galaxy.
* The hottest planet in our solar system is Venus.
* One day on Venus is longer than one year on Venus.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 2
Food and Drink Trivia
* Pound cake got its name from its original recipe, which called for a pound of butter, a pound of sugar, a pound of flour, and a pound of eggs.
* Strawberries are the only fruit with seeds on the outside.
*  A close-up image of a bright red strawberry with visible seeds on its surface. * The fear of cooking is called Mageirocophobia.
Human Body Marvels
   * The average person walks the equivalent of five times around the Earth in their lifetime.
   * Your nose can remember 50,000 different scents.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 3
Word Play
   * "Rhythm" is the longest English word without a vowel.
   * The word "set" has the most definitions of any word in the English language.


 An open dictionary page with a spotlight on the word "set" and its numerous definitions.

Historical Quirks
   * The shortest war in history was between Britain and Zanzibar on August 27, 1896. Zanzibar surrendered after 38 to 45 minutes.
   * Before the invention of the rubber eraser, people used wads of bread.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 4
Nature's Delights
   * Honey never spoils. Archaeologists have found pots of honey in ancient Egyptian tombs that are over 3,000 years old and still perfectly edible.
   *  A glass jar filled with golden honey, next to a wooden honey dipper.    * The northern lights (Aurora Borealis) can be heard, but only faintly, as a crackling sound.
Architectural Wonders
      * The Eiffel Tower can be 15 cm taller during the summer due to thermal expansion.
      * It took less time to build the Empire State Building than it takes to apply for a construction permit in some modern cities.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 5
Inventions and Discoveries
      * The inventor of the Pringles can, Fredric Baur, requested that he be buried in one. His children honored his request.
      * The first computer mouse was made of wood.


 A stylized illustration of a very early, blocky computer mouse made out of wood.

Random Knowledge
      * The total weight of all the ants on Earth is roughly equal to the total weight of all the humans on Earth.
      * The original name for the search engine Google was Backrub.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 6
Animal Powers
      * A cat has 32 muscles in each ear.
      * An octopus has three hearts. Two pump blood through the gills, and one circulates blood to the rest of the body.
      *  A detailed, colorful illustration of a blue-ringed octopus.       * Cows have best friends and get stressed when separated from them.
Geographical Gems
         * Mount Everest grows by about 4 millimeters every year.
         * Istanbul is the only city in the world that is located on two continents (Europe and Asia).
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 7
Movie Magic
         * The actor who voiced E.T. was an 11-year-old girl.
         * The sound effect for the "Lightsaber" in Star Wars was created by combining the hum of a movie projector and the sound of an old television's cathode ray tube.


 A movie projector beaming a light toward a wall, creating an illustration of the projection beam.

Science Surprises
         * If you could drive to the sun at 60 mph, it would take you 173 years.
         * The core of the Earth is hotter than the surface of the sun.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 8
Sports Facts
         * The longest tennis match in history lasted 11 hours and 5 minutes and was played over three days.
         * A golf ball has an average of 336 dimples.


 A close-up of a white golf ball showing the pattern of dimples on its surface.

Everyday Wonders
         * A cloud can weigh over a million pounds.
         * It is physically impossible for pigs to look up at the sky.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 9
Fun with Numbers
         * The number 4 is the only number that has the same amount of letters as its value.
         * The opposite sides of a standard die always add up to seven.


 A collection of different colored dice, clearly showing the numerical arrangement where opposite sides sum to seven.

Name Origins
         * The average lifespan of a taste bud is 10 to 14 days.
         * The fear of long words is called hippopotomonstrosesquippedaliophobia.
Fun Facts Compendium: Page 10
A Mix of the Bizarre
Category
	Fun Fact
	Image
	Deep Ocean
	The Pacific Ocean is wider than the Moon.
	 A side-by-side illustration comparing the width of the Pacific Ocean to the diameter of the Moon.

	Sleep
	Humans spend about one-third of their lives sleeping.
	 A person peacefully sleeping in a bed under a cozy blanket.

	Music
	The "Star-Spangled Banner" is only one of two songs in the world that can be heard only on the radio.


	Trees
	The tallest living tree is named Hyperion, a Coast Redwood in California.
	 A photograph looking straight up the immense trunk of a very tall redwood tree, emphasizing its height.

	Time
	Leap seconds are occasionally added to coordinate clocks with the Earth's slowing rotation.




